# Phase D: Implement dcp-messages subagents.rs — Subagent result expansion

## Background
Port of `lib/subagents/subagent-results.ts` + `lib/messages/inject/subagent-results.ts`. When a sub-agent (Task tool) finishes, its final text output must be injected into the parent conversation. This module extracts sub-agent session IDs, fetches their messages, builds result text, and merges it into the parent's tool output.

## Target file
`crates/dcp-messages/src/subagents.rs`

## Public API
```rust
/// Extracts sessionId from a tool part's metadata. Returns None if missing.
pub fn get_sub_agent_id(part: &Part) -> Option<String>;

/// Builds result text from sub-agent message history:
/// - Filter to assistant messages only
/// - Get last assistant message's text
/// - If 2+ assistant messages AND second-to-last used compress tool → concatenate both
pub fn build_subagent_result_text(messages: &[Message]) -> String;

/// Replaces content inside <task_result>...</task_result> tags with sub-agent result
/// Regex: case-insensitive, non-greedy
pub fn merge_subagent_result(output: &str, sub_agent_result_text: &str) -> String;

/// Iterates messages for completed "task" tool calls:
/// - Skip if in prune set
/// - Check subAgentResultCache for previously fetched results
/// - Extract session ID, fetch messages (via trait), build result, cache and merge
/// - Strip DCP tag hallucinations from merged output
pub fn inject_extended_sub_agent_results(
    state: &mut SessionState,
    messages: &mut Vec<Message>,
    allow_sub_agents: bool,
);
```

## Key algorithm: build_subagent_result_text
The "second-to-last with compress" detection is the key insight: when a subagent compresses its own context, both the pre-compression and post-compression outputs must be captured.

## Key algorithm: merge_subagent_result
Regex: `(?i)(<task_result>\s*)([\s\S]*?)(\s*</task_result>)` — replaces group 2 with new content.

## Tests
- `test_get_sub_agent_id_present` — returns session ID from metadata
- `test_get_sub_agent_id_missing` — returns None
- `test_build_result_text_single_assistant` — last assistant text returned
- `test_build_result_text_with_compress` — concatenates pre+post compress text
- `test_merge_subagent_result_replaces_content` — task_result content replaced
- `test_merge_subagent_result_no_tag` — returns unchanged when no tag
- `test_inject_skips_pruned` — pruned tool calls skipped
- `test_inject_uses_cache` — cached results used without re-fetching

## Dependencies
- Phase C5 (utils.rs) — strip_hallucinations_from_string
- Phase C1 (query.rs) — message filtering
- dcp-state for subagent_result_cache

## Why this matters
Without subagent result expansion, parent conversations lose the detailed output from Task tool calls. The model sees only a truncated result instead of the full sub-agent session. This is especially important when the sub-agent has compressed its own context — both the pre-compress and post-compress text must be preserved.

# Phase C2: Implement dcp-messages shape.rs — Message validation & filtering

## Background
Port of `lib/messages/shape.ts`. Runtime type validation and filtering for message arrays. Ensures all messages conform to the expected shape before processing. These are the safe entry points for data from external sources (API responses, etc).

## Target file
`crates/dcp-messages/src/shape.rs`

## Public API
```rust
/// Type guard: validates message is non-null object with:
/// - info.id: non-empty string
/// - info.sessionID: non-empty string
/// - info.role: "user" or "assistant"
/// - info.time.created: numeric
/// - parts: array
pub fn is_valid_message(msg: &Message) -> bool;

/// Filters an unknown array through is_valid_message, returning a new Vec
pub fn filter_messages(messages: Vec<Message>) -> Vec<Message>;

/// Same filtering but in-place compaction (mutates input, maintains same Vec)
pub fn filter_messages_in_place(messages: &mut Vec<Message>);
```

## Implementation notes
- `filter_messages_in_place` is the zero-allocation variant: uses write index, then truncates
- Both accept potentially invalid data — they are safe entry points
- The validation checks ensure downstream code can safely access fields

## Tests
- `test_is_valid_message_with_valid_user` — valid user message passes
- `test_is_valid_message_with_valid_assistant` — valid assistant message passes
- `test_is_valid_message_empty_id` — empty ID fails
- `test_is_valid_message_invalid_role` — invalid role fails
- `test_filter_messages_removes_invalid` — invalid messages filtered out
- `test_filter_messages_in_place_same_result` — in-place produces same result
- `test_filter_messages_empty_input` — empty input returns empty

## Dependencies
- dcp-messages scaffold (bead 7jq)
- dcp-types for Message

## Why this matters
These are the gatekeepers that prevent malformed messages from reaching the core processing pipeline. A single invalid message could cause a panic in downstream code that assumes fields exist.

# Phase F3: Implement prompt extensions — tool.rs (compress output format)

## Background
Port of `lib/prompts/extensions/tool.ts`. Defines fixed JSON format schemas for the compress tool's output. These are NOT editable via custom prompt overrides because they must match the tool's input validation exactly.

## Target file
`crates/dcp-prompts/src/extensions/tool.rs` (new file)

## Public API
```rust
/// Output format for range-mode compression:
/// { topic: string, content: [{ startId, endId, summary }] }
/// startId/endId are boundary IDs like "mNNNN" or "bN"
pub const RANGE_FORMAT_EXTENSION: &str;

/// Output format for message-mode compression:
/// { topic: string, content: [{ messageId, topic, summary }] }
/// messageId is a raw message ID like "mNNNN"
pub const MESSAGE_FORMAT_EXTENSION: &str;
```

## Implementation
- Two const strings describing JSON output schemas
- Field names must match exactly what the compress output parser expects
- These get appended to the compress tool's description at runtime

## Tests
- `test_range_format_contains_required_fields` — startId, endId, summary, topic, content
- `test_message_format_contains_required_fields` — messageId, topic, summary, content
- `test_formats_are_valid_description_text` — no broken XML, proper structure

## Dependencies
- None — purely static string constants

## Why this matters
These schemas tell the model exactly how to format its compress tool output. The parser that validates compress results expects these exact field names. Any mismatch causes compress to fail silently or produce malformed blocks.
